# CODING_AGENT_TASK.md (template)

> The task contract you hand a coding agent. Self-contained — the agent doesn't need your conversation history.

```markdown
# Task: {{Short title}}

## Context
{{2–3 sentences: why this work matters, what user / system it serves.}}

## Goal
{{One sentence: what success looks like.}}

## Non-goals
- {{out-of-scope thing 1}}
- {{out-of-scope thing 2}}

## Inputs / sources
- Issue: {{link}}
- Related PRs: {{links}}
- Files likely involved: {{paths}}
- Other docs: {{paths}}

## Definition of done
- [ ] {{specific outcome 1}}
- [ ] {{specific outcome 2}}
- [ ] Tests + lint + typecheck pass
- [ ] Smallest diff that achieves the goal
- [ ] PR description complete (Summary / Why / How tested / Risks)

## Constraints
- One concept per PR
- No new top-level dependencies without approval
- High-risk operations (push --force, destructive shell) require approval
- Stay in scope — surface scope creep as a follow-up issue, don't fold it in

## Risks to call out
- {{thing that could go wrong}}
- {{thing not tested}}

## Reference docs
- AGENTS.md
- relevant SOUL.md / TOOLS.md
- {{specific deep dive}}
```

## When to use this

- Cloud / autonomous coding-agent tasks (Codex cloud, etc.)
- Long-running CLI sessions where you want a written contract
- Multi-agent handoffs (planner → worker)

## Tip

The agent reads the task as authoritative. Make the **Definition of done** measurable; vague DoDs produce vague PRs.
